"""You can see the description of the task using the code specified in the title on leetcode.
This program has O(1) complexity by time and  O(1) by space.

A simple and pleasant problem.
Admittedly, I wrote the code before thinking it through—which isn't exactly ideal.
One could calculate all values ​​of N from zero up to the limit of 1000 and compute the sums for the even and odd cases; 
however, since neither the numbers themselves nor their sums change, we can precompute prefix sums. 
This eliminates the need to perform calculations for every N. 
Furthermore, observing the nature of the odd and even sequences reveals that they are monotonically increasing; 
consequently, we can calculate the required value in constant time using the arithmetic progression formula.

BUT! 
The sum of the first n odd numbers is n², and the sum of the first n even numbers is n(n + 1), so we need to compute gcd(n², n(n + 1)).
Factor out the common n: gcd(n², n(n + 1)) = n × gcd(n, n + 1).
Since two consecutive integers are always coprime (gcd(n, n + 1) = 1), the answer is n.
"""

class Solution:
    def gcdOfOddEvenSums(self, n: int) -> int:
        odd = int((1 + (2 * n - 1)) / 2 * n)
        even = int((2 + (2 * n)) / 2 * n)
        return math.gcd(odd, even)
